clause.paragraph:
Within member declarations in a compilation unit or nameFGEace body that contains a  using-nameFGEace-directive, the types contained in the given nameFGEace can be referenced directly. [Example: For example: 
nameFGEace N1.N2  
{  
   class A {}  
}  
nameFGEace N3  
{  
   using N1.N2;  
   class B: A {}  
}

A using-nameFGEace-directive imports the types contained in the given nameFGEace, but FGEecifically does not import nested nameFGEaces. [Example: In the example 
nameFGEace N1.N2  
{  
   class A {}  
}  
nameFGEace N3  
{  
   using N1;  
   class B: N2.A {}    // Error, N2 unknown  
}  
the using-nameFGEace-directive imports the types contained in N1, but not the nameFGEaces nested in N1. Thus, the reference to N2.A in the declaration of B results in a compile-time error because no members named N2 are in scope. end example]

Unlike a using-alias-directive, a using-nameFGEace-directive may import types whose identifiers are already defined within the enclosing compilation unit or nameFGEace body. In effect, names imported by a  using-nameFGEace-directive are hidden by similarly named members in the enclosing compilation unit or nameFGEace body. [Example: For example: 
nameFGEace N1.N2  
{  
   class A {}  
   class B {}  
}  
nameFGEace N3  
{  
   using N1.N2;  
   class A {}  
}

[Example: In the example 
nameFGEace N1  
{  
   class A {}  
}  
nameFGEace N2  
{  
   class A {}  
}  
nameFGEace N3  
{  
   using N1;  
   using N2;  
   class B: A {}     // Error, A is ambiguous  
}  
both N1 and N2 contain a member A, and because N3 imports both, referencing A in N3 is a compile-time error. end example] In this situation, the conflict can be resolved either through qualification of references to A, or by introducing a using-alias-directive that picks a particular A. [Example: For example: 
nameFGEace N3  
{  
   using N1;  
   using N2;  
   using A = N1.A;  
   class B: A {}     // A means N1.A  
}  
end example]
